# Why templated automation fails for order processing

For decades, businesses have tried to automate order processing with templates and rules. Define the expected format, map the fields, and let software extract the data. On paper, it works. In practice, it breaks constantly.

## The template trap

Template-based systems require a fixed layout for each document type. A purchase order from Customer A has the product code in column 3, the quantity in column 5, and the delivery date in the header. The system learns this layout and extracts accordingly.

The problem emerges immediately:

- **Customer A changes their PO format.** A new ERP system, a new procurement manager, or even a software update shifts the columns. The template breaks.
- **Customer B sends free-text emails.** There are no columns. The order is embedded in a paragraph of conversational text, mixed with questions about pricing and delivery windows.
- **Customer C sends handwritten notes.** A warehouse manager scribbles an order on a notepad and photographs it. No template can anticipate every handwriting style and layout.

## The maintenance burden

Even when templates work initially, maintaining them creates an ever-growing cost center. Each customer format requires its own template. Each format change requires manual reconfiguration. A distributor with 500 active customers might need hundreds of templates — and every one of them can break at any time.

The IT team becomes a bottleneck. Business users cannot adjust templates themselves. New customers take days or weeks to onboard because someone has to build their template first.

## Why AI approaches differ

AI-driven order processing does not rely on fixed layouts. Instead, it understands the semantic content of a document. It recognizes that "10 x Widget A" and "Widget A — qty 10" and a handwritten "10 Widget A" all mean the same thing.

This semantic understanding means:

- **No per-customer templates.** The system adapts to any format from any customer.
- **Format changes are invisible.** When a customer updates their PO layout, the AI still understands the content.
- **New customers onboard instantly.** There is no template to build. The first order is processed like the thousandth.

## The real question

The question is not whether to automate order processing — the volume demands it. The question is whether to invest in rigid templates that require constant maintenance, or in AI systems that adapt to the reality of how orders actually arrive: messy, varied, and unpredictable.
